article.description:
Katie Douglas scored 20 points and Margo Dydek had another big game in the middle for Connecticut with
14 rebounds and five blocks to lead the Sun to an 81-69 win over the Seattle Storm on Tuesday.
article.headline: Bird hurt by teammate Jackson with 3 minutes left
article.linkText: Bird breaks nose again in Storm loss at Conn.
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Sue Bird banged the floor in pain and
frustration. The feeling was all too familiar.

Bird and the Seattle Storm had begun rallying from a 19-point
deficit against the Connecticut Sun with 3 minutes left when the
star guard took an elbow from teammate Lauren Jackson, breaking her
nose for the second time in a year.

Clutching a bloody towel, the former UConn star left the game to
rousing ovation, taking much of the momentum with her.

Connecticut held on down the stretch for an 81-69 win Tuesday
night in a rematch of last season's WNBA Finals. Katie Douglas led
the Sun with 20 points and Margo Dydek had another big game in the
middle with 14 rebounds and five blocks.

"Everyone on this team has added someting to their game over
last year," Sun coach Mike Thibault said. "We've got leadership
from every veteran."

And this year, the Sun also have Dydek.

The 7-foot-2 center, acquired in a draft-day trade from San
Antonio, finished with 11 points for her first double-double of the
season. Dydek blocked nine shots, a franchise record, in Saturday's
80-69 win over San Antonio.

"I think having Margo inside is a huge difference," Jackson
said. "She's just playing unbelievable basketball. It's just
another dimension in their game."

The Sun made life miserable early for the 6-foot-5 Jackson, who
finished with 20 points. She was jostled nearly every trip in the
lane and was 4-of-9 from the floor in the first period.

Bird didn't get untracked until the closing minutes of the
period, scoring all six of her first-half points in the final 2:37.
She also provided the spark late in the second half before her
injury.

Bird had just scored four straight points to help Seattle start
climbing back. The Storm had whittled the lead to 10 when Bird was
taken out.

Bird, who played with a broken nose throughout last year's
playoffs, wasn't talking after the game, but team officials said
she is listed day-to-day. The game against the Sun was the first of
four road games in six days for the defending champs.

"We had stretches where people tried, just tried to make
something happen," Storm coach Anne Donovan said. "I think we
just got frustrated with our offense. We didn't stick with it and
try to break it down."

Dydek established her dominance early. She had nine points, six
boards and pair of blocked shots in the first period and altered
many more. Her boards and blocks again helped start Connecticut's
transition game. The Sun, who led by as many as 15 points, had a
50-41 advantage at the break.

Taj McWilliams-Franklin scored 19 points and Nykesha Sales
finished with 15 points, and Lindsay Whalen had eight assists for
Connecticut.

Bird and Betty Lennox each had 12 points for Seattle, which beat
the Sun in the best-of-three finals last season to give the city
its first professional championship in 25 years.

"I don't care anything about what happened last year,"
McWilliams-Franklin said. "I only care what we're doing now."
